Application of these data to the world's population provides very rough estimates of the global burden of critical illness syndromes (table 1
). Of note, these values might underestimate the burden in developing countries, where a higher proportion of deaths is caused by infection and injury. In addition, they assume that the age, sex, risk factor distributions, and critical care capacity are similar to those of the North American populations that generated the epidemiological data. Even in the developed world, epidemiological data for availability of ICU beds are sparse (table 2
).
